{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643341"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17997"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17997"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10711"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64180"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"10218"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27035"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical spine has a number of joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is NOT a joint of the cervical spine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atlantoaxial","Atlantooccipital","Occipitoaxial","Symphyses","Zygapophyseal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical spine includes several important joints that allow for a wide range of motion. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eatlantoaxial\u003C/strong\u003E joint is located between the first and second cervical vertebrae (C1 and C2) and allows for rotation of the head. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eatlantooccipital\u003C/strong\u003E joint is between the occipital bone of the skull and the first cervical vertebra (C1), allowing for nodding movements of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygapophyseal\u003C/strong\u003E joints, also known as facet joints, are synovial joints between the articular processes of adjacent vertebrae and are present throughout the spine, including the cervical region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymphyses\u003C/strong\u003E are a type of cartilaginous joint found in the spine, specifically in the intervertebral discs, but they are not specific to the cervical region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipitoaxial\u003C/strong\u003E joint is not a recognised joint in the cervical spine. The occipital bone articulates with the atlas (C1) at the atlantooccipital joint, not directly with the axis (C2).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cervical spine consists of several joints, including the atlantoaxial, atlantooccipital, and zygapophyseal joints.","The occipitoaxial joint is not a recognised joint in the cervical spine.","Symphyses are a type of joint found in the spine, but not specifically in the cervical region."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health S